“Protection of Civilians challenges in the context of intense warfighting in Ukraine”
Issue brief
Organizational Mission and Vision
The Center for Civilians in Conflict (CIVIC) is an international organization dedicated to
promoting the protection of civilians in conflict. CIVIC envisions a world in which no civilian is
harmed in conflict. Our mission is to support communities affected by conflict in their quest for
protection and strengthen the resolve and capacity of armed actors to prevent and respond to
civilian harm. CIVIC was established in 2003 by Marla Ruzicka, a young humanitarian who
advocated on behalf of civilians affected by the war in Iraq and Afghanistan. Honoring Marla’s
legacy, CIVIC has kept an unflinching focus on the protection of civilians in conflict. Today,
CIVIC has a presence in conflict zones and key capitals throughout the world where it
collaborates with civilians to bring their protection concerns directly to those in power, engages
with armed actors to reduce the harm they cause to civilian populations, and advises
governments and multinational bodies on how to make life-saving and lasting policy changes.
CIVIC’s strength is its proven approach and record of improving protection outcomes for
civilians by working directly with conflict-affected communities and armed actors. At CIVIC, we
believe civilians are not “collateral damage” and civilian harm is not an unavoidable
consequence of conflict—civilian harm can and must be prevented.

Executive Summary
Methodology
This report is based on the secondary analysis of the publicly available information and the
primary analysis of qualitative semi-structured interviews conducted by CIVIC with key
informants. The research was carried out in two stages. During the first stage in January –
Matrch 2023, CIVIC consulted open-source information on the primary trends of harm to
civilians and civil infrastructure, international support to Ukraine, and the AFU specifically, which
effectively contributed to enhancing civilian protection capabilities. The publicly available data
included information from the official websites of international organizations, national
governmental institutions of Ukraine, non-governmental organizations, and media sources. The
gaps identified during this initial research phase helped formulate research questions for the
second phase of the study.
At the second phase of the research, in February – March 2023, the primary data was collected
through expert interviews with representatives of local governments, military commanders,
CIMIC officers, as well as volunteers and civilians. CIVIC conducted interviews with 14
government officials (10 male/4 female), 6 military commanders (brigade commander level) (all
male officers), 13 military officers (8 male/5 female) and 93 CIMIC officers (75 male/ 18
female), 8 volunteers (2 male/6 female), and 164 civilians (36 male/ 128 female). 59 semi-
structured interviews were conducted both in-person and remotely. The rest of the respondents
were covered by 1 on-line and 4 off-line surveys. All participants agreed to speak with CIVIC
under the condition of anonymity. Each interview was assigned a unique number, referenced in
the citations. Citations provide relevant information about the source of the information without
disclosing the personal details of the interviewees’ who shared their observations with CIVIC.
The conclusions and final recommendations of this report are based mostly on the analysis of
the primary data collected from the semi-structured interviews. They are also informed by the
experience of the core author of this report, CIVIC Military Engagement Officer, who served as
a command officer in Territorial Defense Forces in 2022 and other CIVIC Ukraine team
members.

1. Trends of harms to civilians in area of operation
Use of explosive weapons
Since 2014 and most significantly after February 24. 2022 Russia's war against Ukraine
unfortunately continues to reap its bloody harvest, resulting in thousands of deaths among
civilians, destroying the whole cities and devastating vast areas, including environmental
damage, landmine and unexploded ordnances contamination, massive exodus of population
from the country and internal displacement. Since the beginning of Russia's full-scale invasion
of Ukraine, the OHCHR has documented at least 21,965 civilian casualties, including 8,231
deaths and 13,734 injuries.
1
Russian armed forces have indiscriminately targeted residential
areas and repeatedly shelled energy infrastructure, leaving millions of civilians without
electricity, water, and heating during severe winter temperatures. Since February 24, 2022,
bombings and shelling by Russia have destroyed 177 medical facilities and damaged an
additional 1,256 objects.
2
Furthermore, 3,328 educational institutions have been damaged in
Ukraine, including 265 that were completely destroyed.
3
What is characteristic for the war in Ukraine is that no place in Ukraine is safe because of the
type of attacks and weapons used. It is a most intensive war in Europe since World War II from
the perspective of the massive use of artillery by both sides (probably millions of shells were
already used), hundreds of thousands of troops engaged, immensely long frontlines, assaults
upon civilian targets with long range ballistic and cruise missiles, air strikes (both dumb bombs
and guided ordnances), unprecedented combination of land, air and naval warfare combined,
attacks with the use of hundreds of thousands of drones, etc.
In general, harm to civilians attributable to armed conflict in Ukraine can be categorized into
two groups. The first category includes the damage inflicted by Russian forces via strikes
(mostly cruise and ballistic missiles plus kamikaze drones) at the operational and strategic level
targets deep in the rear. The second category pertains to the damage directly inflicted at the
tactical level in the vicinity of the frontline. At the strategic level, long-range cruise missiles
(“Kalibr”, Kh-55(5), Kh-101, Kh-22, “Oniks”, 9K720 “Iskander-K”,) middle-range ballistic missiles
(S-300, “Iskander-M”, “Tochka-U” and alike) and UAV Drones (Iranian designed and made
Shahed) are used to engage targets throughout the whole territory of Ukraine, including the
most distant regions in the West of Ukraine (e.g. strikes to Lviv, Khmelnytsky, Rivne). In
October 2022 – April 2023 a targeted campaign to destroy the energy system of Ukraine was
carried out aimed at deliberate harm to civilians who can have been frozen to death in their
homes if these attacks had succeeded.
At the tactical level, the destruction of the significant parts of some Ukrainian towns and cities
(sometimes almost total annihilation like in the towns of Popasna or Avdiivka) as a result of

endured an almost 10-month siege by Russian forces. Daily attacks on the city resulted in the
destruction of apartment buildings, schools, medical facilities, and other infrastructure. The
once-green city is now transformed into a desert of ruins, covered in dust and debris.
8
These examples underscore the urgent need for the reconstruction of heavily damaged areas,
providing assistance to the affected population, and identifying measures to prevent similar
types of warfare in the future.

threats to civilians. According the AFU CIMIC officer CIVIC interviewed, Russia's information

civilians, has become a significant factor in the current conflict. It was particularly dangerous for
the civilian population when Russian forces had distorted information about evacuations, such
as spreading false or distorted messages about the safety of certain areas or evacuation routes.
This created confusion and danger for civilians who were trying to save themselves or find safe
places, guided by false messages.

safety and the safety of civilian families during evacuations or while seeking a safer place.

Manifestations of harm
The war waged by Russia against Ukraine has extremely serious consequences for the civilian
population, including various types of harm. Based on interviews with civilians, local authorities,
and the militaries, CIVIC has identified four main types of the harm inflicted to the civilian
population:
1. physical harm - deaths, injuries, and long-term disabilities. The most tragic event of any
war is a death of a human being. It is irreversible. Here in Ukraine thousands of

by shelling, exchanges of fire, ERWs and UXOs. These fatalities has irreparable
consequences for the individuals themselves, and left eternal scars on hearts of their
families’ members, and Ukrainian society, in general, because it is for many years –
since proclamation of its independence in 1991 or even earlier – since the end of the
Second World War in 1945 Ukraine and its citizens have never been involved in any
armed conflict, hence considering the loss of life as caused by war as implausible.
Even more civilians suffered serious injuries as related to the war, including gunshot
wounds, blast injuries, fragmentation injuries, or other injuries related to warfighting.
Military medics CIVIC talked with report various types of injuries among civilians. They

severe head and neck traumas. The consequences of such injuries often lead to

Overall, the war in Ukraine has caused significant material damage to the civilian population.
The destruction of homes, shops, hospitals, schools, and other infrastructure facilities has

3. Psychological harm: The warfighting also had a tremendous psychological impact over
civilians, men, women, boys and girls. Continuous fear, anxiety, stress, and trauma associated
with combat actions lead to development of such health issues as post-traumatic stress
disorder, depression, and other mental health problems. These problems, in their turn, affect
profoundly the quality of life, relationships, and overall well-being of Ukrainian civilians. The
impact of the mental health problems has been increasing as the conflict continues with no
foreseeable solution in future and lasting for more than 19 months (as of the time when this
report is released).

4. Social harm: Military operations also bring social harm to social protection of civilians. This
includes the loss of access to essential social services such as education, healthcare, housing,
and employment. The war in Ukraine also forces people to leave their homes and seek refuge in
other areas of Ukraine (internally displaced people) or other countries (refugees). There are
nearly 5.1 million internally displaced people in Ukraine (as of May 2023), more than 6.2 million
refugees from Ukraine have been recorded globally (as of July 2023) and approximately 17.6
million people are in need of humanitarian assistance (as of July 2023)

.
Within the current research CIVIC conducted a survey among civilians on civilians’ self-
perception of their security and vulnerability , there is a prevailing subjective perception of their
average level of security. The most noticeable vulnerability is observed in the material sphere,
with an average rating of 4.4 on a ten-point scale, where 10 represents maximum security and
1 represents maximum vulnerability. Physical security is rated at 4.5, while psychological
security is rated at 4.7, indicating the development of psychological defense mechanisms
against traumatizing events. Overall, the surveyed individuals predominantly hold a realistic
understanding of the level of danger. CIVIC can state that despite the challenges, Ukrainian
civilians developed and displayed resilience and powerful adaptation strategies to deal with the

2. Response of the AFU to minimize harm to civilians in area of operation
Since the start of the full-scale invasion by the Russian Federation, the implementation of
measures to prevent and reduce harm to the civilian population has become extremely crucial.
In this context, the AFU plays a significant role by devoting great attention to the protection
and safety of civilians in their respective AoO. According to a military commander interviewed
by CIVIC,
"Preventing human suffering, preserving lives, and ensuring the maximum possible
conditions of safety for civilians have become one of the primary tasks for the military."
36
Using
the data from the survey conducted among military personnel, local authorities, and the civilian
population, CIVIC has identified the following key areas of activities undertaken by the AFU to
protect civilians:
1. The adaptation of the civil-military cooperation system of the AFU involves several positive
changes in the structure and functions of the Civil-Military Cooperation (CIMIC) units aimed at
improving assistance and protection for civilians. One key aspect of the AFU adaptation is a
structural development that enhances interaction with local authorities and civil society
organizations. Another positive aspect of CIMIC adaptation is the review and improvement of its
functions. This includes the development and implementation of mechanisms for rapid response
to threats to the civilian population, such as early warning systems, evacuation, and civilian
protection. Additionally, the enhancement of functions entails raising the level of training and
preparedness for CIMIC officers to enable them to operate more effectively in complex
environments. The third crucial stage of CIMIC adaptation involves improving the legal
framework, including the development of a new CIMIC doctrine and other documents.

Obviously, AFU CIMIC system is not perfect and there are still gaps and shortcomings.
However, the aforementioned changes represent positive steps towards the protection of the
civilian population. For further details on this topic refer to “The Role of Civil-Military
Cooperation in Protection of Civilians: The Ukraine Experience” CIVIC policy brief

3. Data collection on harm to civilians. A positive achievement has been the implementation of
IHL (International Humanitarian Law) violations tracking and civilian harm tracking Orders
issued by within the AFU in March 2022 and September 2022. According to these orders, all
subordinate command structures report on incidents of harm to civilians and their respective
areas of responsibility on a monthly basis. Within these reports, they must specify the causes
and circumstances of civilian casualties and the destruction of civilian infrastructure. These
initiatives reflect a growing commitment to transparency, accountability, and protection of
civilians (PoC) during military operations conducted by the AFU.
It should be noted that this reporting is limited so far only to the cases when harm is inflicted
by Russia and the landmine/ERW incidents. An analysis of the harm caused by Ukrainian forces
has not been practiced so far. First, it is not feasible to obtain such information from the
territories controlled by the Russian Forces and the frontline did not move much since
November 2022. Secondly, while being interviewed by CIVIC, AFU officers insisted that the AFU
does not practice deliberate use of firepower that may affect civilians.

4. Joint training and exercise with local authorities. Prior to the full-scale invasion of Ukraine by
Russia in 2022, the AFU regularly conducted training exercises at all levels to practice the
evacuation and protection of the civilian population. These exercises also involved the local
authorities, police representatives, and the State Emergency Service (SES). During such training
sessions, they practiced cooperation and coordination during evacuation scenarios.

there simply wasn't time or opportunity for them.

roles and actions of local authorities and the AFU. Representatives from the SES and the police
are also involved in these exercises to practice joint actions and improve evacuation plans.

humanitarian crisis in their area of responsibility. As one of the AFU commanders said,

these measures intuitively, on their own initiative."

3. The challenges faced by AFU in assisting civilians
According to the CIVIC survey results, 95% of military personnel responded that the main
problem they face is the presence of the civilian population in the active combat areas. The
presence of civilians creates additional challenges for the military, which the commanders must

address while carrying out their battle missions. Based on the CIVIC survey, the following main
factors related to the presence of civilians in conflict areas were identified:
1. Risk to civilians: Military personnel must adhere to the rules of international humanitarian
law, including protection of civilians during military operations. But despite all potential
precautions by the military, presence of civilians in a AoO maximizes risks to their safety.
Moreover, civilians can be inadequately informed on the risks related to staying in the
warfighting zones and thus act spontaneously, potentially subjecting themselves to harm or
those they care about (children, the elderly).
2. Limited freedom of action: The presence of civilians in an AoO obviously restricts the
military's ability to conduct operations without restrictions. They must avoid civilian objects that
are meant to be protected and consider the potential consequences of their actions over
civilians. The military cited these limitations as an important factor that has a significant impact
over planning and execution of military operations.
3. Need for humanitarian assistance: Military personnel are also tasked with addressing the
provision of humanitarian aid to the civilian population, especially when no other aid providers
are available or the areas are inaccessible due to the hostilities. This factor may require the
military to mobilize additional resources and efforts, diverting their time and resources from
implementing their primary military objectives.
Taking these factors into account, CIVIC recommends that the military forces must engage in
careful planning and coordination on protection of civilians within their regular planning and
preparing process to minimize risks to the civilian population and ensure their safety and well-
being.
The active combat areas are actually death zones for civilians in Ukraine. One of the ways how
the military can contribute to POC is their evacuations to other regions of Ukraine. The efforts
of the military and local administrations should be focused on facilitating the evacuation process
to the maximum extent possible. However, there are multiple cases mentioned by CIVIC
interviewees when civilians deliberately refuse to leave their homes in the active combat zones.
Based on the survey answers from both civilians and military personnel, CIVIC identified the
main reasons why civilians refuse to evacuate:
1. Reluctance to leave their property: Many civilians were unwilling to leave their homes
because it is everything they have.

domestic animals, and agricultural assets – the only things they have.

their property from looting. If there were multiple individuals residing in the residence, a
husband or father would stay behind to prevent theft and looting. The rest of the family
members would evacuate to other regions of Ukraine.
64

chose to stay at home due to fears of being robbed by their neighbors.

1. Effective International Support and Assistance in Enhancing AFU Capabilities for Protection of
Civilians and Civilian Harm Mitigation
The international support provided to Ukraine during the full-scale invasion by Russia has
proven to be extremely important in resisting a much stronger adversary. In 2021, Russia's GDP
was nine times larger than Ukraine's ($1.778 trillion
90
versus $200 billion
91
). Additionally, Russia
has a population three times larger than Ukraine (146 million versus 44 million).
92
Since the
beginning of the war, Ukraine’s international partners have allocated over 113 billion euros to
Ukraine. This amount includes financial, humanitarian, and military assistance from foreign
governments.
93
More than 40 countries have become donors to Ukraine, specifically the EU
member states, other members of the G7, as well as Australia, South Korea, Turkey, Norway,
New Zealand, Switzerland, China, Taiwan, and India. The European Union has allocated nearly
52 billion euros, while the assistance from the United States reached 48 billion euros. Half of
the allocated funds consist of financial aid, another third is military assistance, and the
remaining portion is humanitarian support.
94
Therefore, international support has played and
continues to play a crucial role in providing necessary resources, supporting the civilian
population, and strengthening Ukraine's defense capabilities.
An important component of the international support from Western partners is also opening of
borders to Ukrainians who lost their homes and have been forced to leave areas affected by the
conflict. As it was mentioned earlier, the number of the refugees coming to European countries
from Ukraine since the start of the full-scale Russian invasion has reached almost 7 million
people. Poland has received the largest number of refugees, approximately 1.5 million
individuals. Other countries that have received a significant number of Ukrainian displaced
persons include Germany, the Czech Republic, Italy, Spain, Bulgaria, France, Romania, and
Slovakia.
95
The acceptance of refugees from Ukraine also has a significant military aspect.
Providing shelter to those who relocated from Ukraine or from the most affected areas to safer
regions of Ukraine help Ukrainian military forces to focus on their military tasks, because these
people receive care from non-military actors if re-located. Thus, according to the opinion of
CIVIC interviewees among the AFU military, ensuring successful relocation of IDPs and refugees
contributes to more effective military operations and helps reduce casualties among both
civilians and military personnel.

funds to strengthen its economy and infrastructure, organize humanitarian aid, and implement
crucial social programs. As of June 2023, the volume of international aid exceeded $170 billion
since the start of the full-scale invasion.

displaced persons (IDP).

It is clear that international humanitarian assistance is not directly related to the PoC capacity of

mention in this brief since it indirectly enhances the AFU's ability to protect civilians through the
following directions:
- Protection of civilian population: Providing humanitarian aid prioritizes the goal of
protecting civilians in armed conflicts. This includes ensuring safety, shelter, food,
medical assistance, and other essential needs. Protecting the civilian population allows
military forces to focus on their military tasks, knowing that the civilian population is
receiving the necessary assistance.
- Moral support: Humanitarian aid also has a significant psychological aspect. It
demonstrates solidarity and support from the international community, showing that
people are not left abandoned and that their needs and suffering are acknowledged.
This can strengthen the morale of both the civilian population and the military personnel
who feel supported and recognized for their work.
- Reduction of humanitarian crisis: Humanitarian aid contributes to the reduction of a
humanitarian crisis by meeting the basic needs of the population. This can help mitigate
the negative consequences of the conflict, improve living conditions, and ensure stability
in affected areas. Such alleviation of the humanitarian situation can reduce tension and
conflict situations, providing a more favorable environment for military operations.

Military assistance provided to Ukraine during the invasion by Russia plays a crucial role not
only in ensuring defense capabilities and resisting a stronger adversary but also in reducing
casualties among the civilian population. This assistance primarily includes the supply of high-
precision weapons and ammunition, air defense and missile defense systems, reconnaissance
assets, demining equipment, and tools, as well as training and consultations from highly skilled
military experts.
The majority of the military personnel interviewed by CIVIC (around 95%) stated that the
primary military assistance to the AFU, contributing to the reduction of civilian casualties, is
high-precision weaponry. According to one of the military commanders,
"Supplying the AFU
with precision weaponry and high-tech equipment leads to a decrease in civilian casualties.
Modern weaponry, despite its lethality, is far less harmful to the civilian population."
101
An artillery unit commander, who was stationed in the Kharkiv region, provided a vivid example:
"Russia utilizes outdated Soviet-era weaponry. In order to target a location near or within a
populated area, they employ an artillery battery (6 guns) and a large quantity of ammunition.
This results in minimal military success but leads to destruction and civilian casualties around
the target. On the other hand, our use of the high-precision artillery projectile M982 Excalibur
allows us to destroy enemy stationary vehicles at a distance of up to 40 km with a single
shot."
102
It is worth mentioning the MLRS HIMARS and M270 systems that were provided to the AFU as
well. According to the commander of a mechanized battalion,
"These multiple rocket launcher
systems excel in precision. They fire guided missiles, targeting one missile per objective with an
accuracy deviation of just a few meters. In contrast, Soviet-era Uragan and Smerch rocket
systems cover an area with a dispersion of up to 1500 meters. A notable example of HIMARS'
accuracy was the destruction of up to 400 occupiers located in a building in the city of Makiivka
(Donetsk region). Importantly, other nearby objects of civilian infrastructure remained
unaffected."

that
"Interaction and exchange of reconnaissance information with NATO are crucial for

operations."

casualties, enhances situational awareness, and helps to preserve critical infrastructure.

Conclusions and Recommendations
1. Relevant Lessons from Ukraine for NATO Militaries in Preparing for Protection of Civilians and
Civilian Harm Mitigation in the Future
This armed conflict in Ukraine is unprecedented in its scale and intensity on the European
continent since the Second World War. No NATO member country has experienced combat on
its own territory since 1945 (with the exception of some countries in the former Yugoslavia).
This stark reality underscores the importance of studying valuable lessons from the ongoing
conflict in Ukraine. As the conflict escalates, there is a critical need to enhance the
preparedness of NATO countries for such high-intensity conflicts, particularly in the realm of
civilian protection. The conflict in Ukraine serves as a vivid reminder that traditional security
paradigms are questionable and require a comprehensive review of military strategies, training,
and exercises. By analyzing the lessons learned from the Ukrainian conflict, NATO countries can
gain a better understanding of the complexities and unique challenges associated with
contemporary armed conflicts.
The most valuable lesson that NATO countries can learn from the war in Ukraine lies in the
necessity of conducting a thorough analysis of the practices employed by the AFU in protection
of civilians. This analysis should be carried out without the traditional approaches inherent to
NATO's and member countries’ military doctrines. The previous conflicts, such as in
Afghanistan, serve as examples that some NATO approaches in the context of civilian protection
should be re-thought and re-configured. It is worth noting that the AFU practices in this area far
from being model ones, because the AFU also learn by doing and make errors. However, a
conflict of this magnitude serves as an invaluable source of lessons learned and demands a
deep and objective analysis. To that end, NATO should establish a dedicated body focused on
protection of civilians lessons learned from Russian-Ukrainian war, where the Ukrainian military
125
CIVIC interview with CIMIC officer #18, Kyiv, May 2023.
126
CIVIC interview with representative of Kharkiv regional administration #55, Kharkiv, April 2023.
28
personnel can share their lessons learned and practical examples. To exchange experiences, it
is necessary to invite direct participants of the conflict, such as those with whom CIVIC has
engaged during this research.
CIVIC considers the establishment of effective interaction between local authorities and the
military forces as an important lesson that NATO countries should learn from Ukraine's
experience. In the context of PoC, such interaction is extremely crucial as it encompasses not
only coordination of actions when the threats are immediate, but also planning other measures
in advance, including evacuation of civilians from the affected areas. Additionally, a significant
element is the effort coordination during the distribution and delivery of humanitarian
assistance to civilians in conflict-affected areas. This interaction, information exchange, and
joint planning enables a swift and coordinated response to threats, ensuring the effective
protection of civilians.
The CIMIC officers of the AFU play a pivotal role in this process. Since the beginning of Russia's
full-scale invasion of Ukraine, the CIMIC officers faced new tasks and challenges. CIMIC officers
acted as key intermediaries between local authorities and military commanders, ensuring
effective communication and collaboration between them. This required flexibility, quick
responsiveness, and the ability to adapt to rapidly changing circumstances. Furthermore, the
new challenges demanded adaptation and implementation of changes to the structure and
functions of the CIMIC system. For more information, please refer to the CIVIC report "The Role
of Civil-Military Cooperation in Protection of Civilians: the Ukraine Exeprience.
127
NATO countries must actively consider the experience of the AFU CIMIC , as it provides unique
insights into the real-life experience of confronting a stronger adversary. This can assist NATO
countries in enhancing their PoC capabilities and improving the effectiveness of their military
operations in future. This experience will help to avoid making mistakes and effectively protect
and assist civilians caught in armed conflicts.
It is also important to emphasize that providing informational support to civilians during the
armed conflicts is crucial. Local authorities and the military should maintain constant
communication with the civilian population. In addition, it is necessary to conduct awareness-
raising activities, give the necessary instructions and advice to civilians on how to act in
different dangerous situations. This will reduce the harm that can be caused to civilians during
military operations. Such an approach instills confidence among civilians that they are being
cared for. CIVIC believes that effective informational support to the civilian population in highly
intense warfare is a fundamental factor in ensuring their security and protection.
Tracking and documenting harm caused to civilians and civilian infrastructure during armed
conflict has several important purposes. It allows to assess the scale and nature of the harm
caused, which is important for determining violations of international humanitarian law and
human rights. Recording these facts provides an evidence basis for further investigation and
bringing the perpetrators to justice.
The Armed Forces of Ukraine play an important role in this process. The AFU has implemented
a monitoring and documentation system for cases of violations of IHL that result in harm to the
civilian population and civilian infrastructure. This includes registering incident reports,
collecting testimonies from affected individuals, capturing photos and videos, and gathering
127
The Role of Civil-Military Cooperation in Protection of Civilians: the Ukraine Exeprience CIVIC
report.
29
evidence at the scene of events. The role of the AFU is to ensure the objectivity and credibility
of information regarding the inflicted harm and human rights violations..
Lessons learned in tracking and recording harm to civilians and civilian infrastructure are
important for the future. Based on this experience, NATO countries can develop methodologies
and procedures for monitoring, recording and documenting harm during armed conflict. This
will contribute to strengthening the understanding and adherence to international standards in
the protection of civilians, as well as provide means for effective investigation and holding
responsible parties accountable. Such an approach will enhance the protection of rights and the
safety of the civilian population in future conflicts.
2. Integrating Lessons from Ukraine: Enhancing NATO Training and Exercises for Effective PoC
and CHM in High-Intensity Conflicts
NATO can draw on certain lessons from Ukraine's experience in planning and conducting its
own exercises and training to enhance the PoC capability of its forces. Some of the issues that
can be incorporated into the exercise scenario include:
1. Realistic scenarios: It is recommended to design realistic scenarios that reflect the way
Russia would use its armed forces in causing harm to the civilian population. Special attention
should be given to massive missile attacks throughout the country and the indiscriminate use of
imprecise artillery and Multiple Launch Rocket Systems (MLRS) in the frontline populated areas,
which inflict the most harm to the civilian population.
2. Solution development: It is recommended to develop solutions aimed at preventing the
enemy from using its artillery, which poses the greatest threat to civilian casualties. An example
could be the HIMARS system used to destroy enemy’s artillery ammunition depots. It is
important to be creative and conduct numerous war games with a focus on the impact on the
civilian population, while also involving Ukrainian experts with real practical experience.
3. Joint planning: It involves the participation of all defense and security players, as well as
governmental authorities, in the exercises. At the strategic level, the exercises should focus on
training the coordination between military and governmental entities responsible for the
protection and evacuation of the population. At the operational and tactical levels, the training
scenarios should include situations where effective interaction and coordination need to be
established between local authorities and military commands.
4. Civilian environment assessment: It is recommended to conduct a thorough assessment of
the civilian environment during the exercise design. The assessment should be carried out not
only by the units responsible for the civil affairs, such as J9 (CIMIC), but also by all other units
involved in the planning and execution of the exercises, such as J-2 (intelligence), J-5
(planning), J-3 (operations), etc. The Military Decision-Making Process (MDMP) drills should
include elements aimed at protecting and mitigating civilian casualties.
5. Evacuation and safety of civilians: Scenarios must include tasks to organize the evacuation of
civilians from the affected areas, ensure their safety during the conflict, and allocate resources
for their protection.
6. Technological solutions: It is recommended to develop and apply technological solutions to
develop best practices. This includes software for war gaming with a detailed analysis of the
impact on the civilian population, as well as artificial intelligence for data analysis.
30
In summary, these recommendations aim to enhance the capability of NATO countries and
other stakeholders to protect civilians in high-intensity armed conflicts. By leveraging the
lessons learned from Ukraine, involving Ukrainian experts, and applying technological solutions,
NATO countries and other stakeholders can develop effective PoC approaches and strategies.
Integration of cooperation between local authorities and military commanders, organization of
civilian evacuation, providing information support to the civilian population, and damage
assessment are also crucial elements that should be included in training scenarios for NATO
countries. This will facilitate further exchange of experience and improvement of practices in
the field of PoC and CHM.
